{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"0332c763-e58a-418b-8fac-b9ebc46faf68","content":"The best approach is `dotnet-trace` with the CPU profiling profile:\n\n```bash\n# Install the tool (if not already in the container)\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-trace\n\n# Find your app's PID\ndotnet-trace ps\n\n# Collect a 30-second CPU trace\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:30\n```\n\nThis produces a `.nettrace` file you can analyze in **Visual Studio**, **PerfView**, or convert to speedscope format:\n\n```bash\ndotnet-trace convert trace.nettrace --format Speedscope\n```\n\n**Tips:**\n- If you can't install tools in the container, use a [sidecar/ephemeral container](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/core/diagnostics/dotnet-trace#collect-using-an-ephemeral-container) or copy the tool binary in.\n- For production, prefer `--duration` or `Ctrl+C` to keep trace size manageable.\n- If you need OS-level context (kernel stacks, off-CPU time), use `dotnet-trace collect --profile cpu-sampling -- perf` or `perf record` directly, but `dotnet-trace` is usually sufficient and lowest-friction.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"12ae7d96-439b-46cd-9b62-64f56c58250f","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking for guidance on collecting a CPU trace from a .NET 8 application running in a Kubernetes pod on Linux. This is a knowledge/advice question, not a code change task. I'll provide a concise answer with the recommended approach.","outputTokens":376,"requestId":"CB0C:21003C:1CE8C48:200FCE8:6A05259F"},"id":"a60653e2-b5a5-4ad5-b3b2-7bab2c04a37f","timestamp":"2026-05-14T01:30:31.071Z","parentId":"239a6dc9-33c3-49ab-9483-87defd616366"}
